description: A site known mainly through metal detecting, small finds, aerial photography, and quarrying. Late Iron Age coins show have been used to suggest that the site was a ritual centre in the Iron Age, and crop marks that show a square enclosure have been used to suggest the presence of a possible shrine or temple during the Roman period.
bibliography: Curteis, Jackson, and Markham. “Titchmarsh Late Iron Age and Roman Settlement.” Northamptonshire Archaeology 28 (2000).
Martyn, Blick, Brindle, and et al. “Titchmarsh (Northamptonshire).” The Rural Settlement of Roman Britain: an online resource, 2015. https://doi.org/10.5284/1030449.
